# Code for 1 : Data Entry

# Read data in
alldata = read.csv("combinedData.csv")
# Remove unwanted observations
data = alldata[alldata$DRG.Definition %in% c("192 - CHRONIC OBSTRUCTIVE PULMONARY DISEASE W/O CC/MCC", 
    "293 - HEART FAILURE & SHOCK W/O CC/MCC", "536 - FRACTURES OF HIP & PELVIS W/O MCC", 
    "638 - DIABETES W CC"), ]
# Make Urban a factor
data$Urban = factor(data$Urban, levels = 0:5, labels = c("UR Mix", "R Regions", 
    "RU Clusters", "U Clusters", "U Combo", "U Areas"))
# Calculate how much a patient pays
data$PatientPays = data$Average.Total.Payments - data$Average.Medicare.Payments
# Calculate the percentage of what a patient pays
data$PctPatientPays = data$PatientPays/data$Average.Total.Payments * 100
# Create a new factor vector by crossing Urban and regions
data$urbanByRegions = data$Urban:data$regions
# Drop unused levels
data = droplevels.data.frame(data)
# Print out summary
print(summary(data))

4 : Perform inference to evaluate the difference between the groups

# Code for 4 : Perform inference to evaluate the difference between the groups

# Set up functions/objects for use in later code chunks

# Proceding with permutation method to simulate for p-values in pairwise testing:    

# function to retrive the t-statistic from 2 groups    
t.statistic = function(x, y) {
  return(t.test(x, y)$statistic)
}

# professor's function from hw 2 (does a permutation test with a size repetitions sample)  
permutation.test <- function(group1,group2, FUN, repetitions){
  makePermutedStats<-function(){
      sampled <- sample(1:length(c(group1,group2)), size=length(group1),replace=FALSE)
      return(FUN(c(group1,group2)[sampled], c(group1,group2)[-sampled]))
  }
  stat.obs <- FUN(group1,  group2)
  stat.permute <-replicate(repetitions,makePermutedStats()) 
  p.value <- sum(stat.permute >= stat.obs) / repetitions
  return(list(p.value=p.value,observedStat=stat.obs,permutedStats=stat.permute))
}
# function to call permutation.test with a pair (x), dataframe (df), and variable of interest (pay)  
permtestFun<-function(x, df, pay){
    group1<-df[,pay][df[,'urbanByRegions'] == x[1]]
    group2<-df[,pay][df[,'urbanByRegions'] == x[2]]
    permutation.test(group1,group2,t.statistic, 1000)
}
# retrive values from a list  
get_vals = function(list, index = 1) { 
  sapply(list,FUN='[[', i = index)
}
# get test statistics from permulation tests (Create list of all p.values for each diagnosis' pairwise testing in a list)
get_stats = function(pct = F) {
  if (pct) pay = 'PctPatientPays' else pay = 'PatientPays'
  lapply(lapply(dfs, FUN = function(df) apply(X = pairs, MARGIN = 2, FUN = permtestFun, df = df, pay = pay)), FUN = get_vals)
}


# load in iterators package for eash of title change  
require(iterators) 
## Loading required package: iterators
# create function to plot p-values together (with a transformation using the log of the values)  
plot.p = function(list, correct = F, ylab = 'log(p.value)') {
  par(mfrow = c(2, 2), mar = c(2,5,2,1))
  # create an iterable for ease of title plot change  
  titles = iter(c('192', '293', '536', '638')) 
  # for loop to iterate through every diagnosis group  
  for (group in list) { 
    # if bonferroni corrections are specified to use, adjust the p values accordingly  
    if (correct == F) p.values = group
    else { 
      p.values = pmin(group * length(group), 1)
      ylab = paste('log(p.value *', length(group), ')')
    }
    p.values = log(p.values)
    plot(seq(length(p.values)), p.values, col = sapply(p.values, FUN = function(x) {if (x < log(.05)) 'red' else 'black'}), # make p-values that reject red
         xaxt = 'n', xlab = '', ylab = ylab , main = nextElem(titles))
    # draw the alpha value line  
    abline(a = log(.05), b = 0, lty =2, lwd =2) 
  }
}


# Code for making 95% Confidence Intervals using the bootstrap method  
bootstrap.ci = function(x, df, pay, correct = F) {
  group1 = df[,pay][df[,'urbanByRegions'] == x[1]]
  group2 = df[,pay][df[,'urbanByRegions'] == x[2]]
  obs = t.statistic(x = group1, y = group2)
  # function to simulate one bootstrap
  once = function(){
    group1 = sample(group1, length(group1), repl = T)
    group2 = sample(group2, length(group2), repl = T)
    return(t.statistic(x = group1, y = group2))
  }
  #simulate 1000 bootraps
  bootstrap.stats = replicate(1000, once())
  # account for whether or not I want a bonferonni correction
  if(correct) level = .05/66 else level = .05
  confidence.interval = quantile(bootstrap.stats, probs = c(level/2, 1 - level/2))
  return(c(confidence.interval[1], obs, confidence.interval[2]))
}

# load in gplots package  
require(gplots) 
## Loading required package: gplots
## 
## Attaching package: 'gplots'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     lowess
plot.ci = function(list, correct = F){
  # Create iterable for ease of title change
  titles = iter(c('192', '293', '536', '638')) 
  # plot CI's for each diagnosis
  for (m in list){
    plotCI(m[2,], ui = m[3,], li = m[1,], main = paste(nextElem(titles), 'CIs'), col = apply(m, 2, FUN = function(x) {if (0 > x[1] & 0 <x[3]) 'black' else 'red'}), pch = 19, xaxt = "n", xlim = c(0, 67))
    abline(h = 0, lty = 2) # make line at y=0 
  }
}

# separate dataframe into a list of four separate data frames for each diagnosis    
dfs = lapply(X = lapply(X = levels(exclude$DRG.Definition), FUN = function(x) exclude[exclude$DRG.Definition == x,]), droplevels.data.frame)
# create matrix of all possible pairs in urbanByRegions  
pairs = combn(x =levels(exclude$urbanByRegions), m = 2)

Comments on 4:

The first four plots of each section of the variables are of the p-values of all pairwise testing using a permutation test based on the t-statistic, then the following four plots are the same plot but with Bonferronni corrections applied to every p-value. Then there are 4 confidence interval plots that were generated through the bootstrap method and also based on the t-statistic. Following that, are the confidence interval plots but with Bonferroni corrections applied.
As evidenced by the plots of the p-values without Bonferroni corrections, several individual tests (excluding the PatientPays 536 diagnosis group which has 0 that reject the null hypothesis) reject the null hypotheses at a 5% \(\alpha\) level. However, when the Bonferroni corrections are applied, none of the individual tests reject the null hypotheses. Since this is the case with the Bonferroni corrections, I conclude that there is no difference between any of the groups in my pairwise testings.
I also see a similar trend in the bootstrap confidence intervals for PatientPays. Without Bonferroni corrections, there is a similar rate of confidence intervals that do not include 0 (as compared to the permutation tests), with the 536 diagnosis group having 0 in its confidence intervals everytime. However, unlike the permutation tests, Bonferroni corrections do not cause 0 to be in all of the confidence intervals; it increases the proportion that do have 0 in the diagnosis groups 192 and 193 and causes 0 to to be in all of the 638 confidence intervals.
In the PctPatientPays variable, there are significant differences in the confidence intervals when compared to PatientPays. There is overall a higher rate of 0 not present in the intervals and while Bonferroni corrections do have an effect on the rate of intervals containing 0, there is not an overwhelming increase as what happened with the PatientPays variable.
For the confidence intervals that I have created, I would conclude that there are differences for the pairs with confidence intervals with Bonferroni corrections applied that do not have 0 in the interval.

5 : Comment on the overall analysis

Overall, I think that my analysis was alright with the terms that I still dont know many of the consequences of choosing the tests that I had chosen to do in the course of the project. As I did this project, there were several parts that didnt seem right, so I made corrections to the code. At first, I made a histogram of PatientPays without a log transformation and it was missing a lot of the underlying data that was masked by the bin sizing, so I decided to use a log transformation so that the visualization would be cleaner and without that many bins. Also, I noticed in the violin plots (and the contingency tables) that there were several categories that had caused a clipped violin plot and this made me think about whether or not this category would be dependable in creating an accurate hypothesis test since the sample size of such observations was so small. Removing the 1, ,3, and 4 levels of Urban also seemed neccessary, but also it was unclear as to what removing them from the analysis would do to the overall hypothesis testing and confidence interval accuracy.
This analysis of the difference in what a patient can pay was obviously limited in the fact that the costs of the patients were based on their health and condition (we do not know much about the patients health conditions or what other factors caused a lower/higher cost). The pay is also affected by the type of institute that the treatment was done in, and that affects the pay in various ways. An additional factor is that the time of stay in the institution is not recorded in the data. This can create major differences in the observations as staying longer before a patient is discharged can result in higher costs. Overall, not taking in the account of the situation of the patients creates a big limitation for the effectiveness of this analysis.
There is also the problem of the observations for a group being too small to make an accurate analysis, such as our removal of the levels in Urban, and other problems discussed before.
Since there were many limitations in this data, I would consider trying to find a different data set that includes more variables and more observations to cover regions with little data. I would also want to try doing a separate analysis of the different types of institutes and how it affects the pay.
